      "widgets_values": [
        "VIEWPORT + EXPORT CHECKS (Output Desk holds all the viewport buttons \u2014 the viewport node itself is render-only):\n\n1. Hit \ud83d\udcfd Project, then dolly/orbit in \u2014 the hangar reassembles from the three chained clean-plate bands exactly like the previous example.\n2. Camera Path: click \ud83c\udfa5 Camera Path, pick a preset (e.g. Orbit Left) from the dropdown, click Apply Preset, then \u23fa Bake Proxy Path. This fills the viewport's camera_path/path_frames outputs and re-queues automatically \u2014 AtlasExportCameraPathUSD downstream needs this to have run at least once (camera_path is None until a bake has happened; the export node no-ops and passes the solve through unchanged if camera_path.keyframes is empty).\n3. AtlasExportCameraPathUSD writes camera_path.usda \u2014 a time-sampled Usd.TimeCode-keyed animated camera, importable straight into Maya/Houdini/Blender's USD stage.\n4. AtlasExportNuke writes a Nuke Python script whose Read node points at the real ACEScg EXR (not this graph's ComfyUI-side sRGB-Display preview) \u2014 open the generated .py and confirm the file/colorspace knobs before treating this as verified.\n5. AtlasExportSolveJSON's output JSON should contain a populated \"source_plate\" object (image_path = the EXR, colorspace = ACEScg, bit_depth = 32f, is_proxy = false) plus all three clean-plate ProjectionSources \u2014 the same full pipeline validated end to end from a single JSON.\n6. Open nuke_projection.nk (or .py) in Nuke: ScanlineRender should show the real hangar geometry (torn at depth discontinuities), not a flat floor \u2014 confirms AtlasExportReliefMesh's obj_path reached AtlasExportNuke's relief_mesh_obj_path input and ReadGeo2 is live-projected onto correctly."
      ]
